In natural language processing, sentence processing involves analyzing the structure and meaning of sentences in text. The goal of sentence processing is to understand the sentence in its entirety, identify its constituent parts and determine their relationships, and extract the relevant semantic and syntactic information for the analysis. Sentence processing typically involves tokenization, entity extraction, part-of-speech taggers, word embeddings, and syntax analysis. For example, in the sentences "I see my dog every morning", the word "my" is an article, and "a" is an adjective. Similarly, the word "I had a good time with my friends" has an adverb "good" that modifies the verb "I had", which is an example of an adjective clause. Word embeddings are used to capture the relationships between words in a sentence, and a sentiment analysis is often used to determine the sentiment of the text.
The sentence processing workflow consists of the following steps: tokenization, named entity recognition, sentence splitting, syntax analysis, information retrieval, and natural language understanding. Sentence processing may involve pre-processing steps such as tokenization and removing punctuation and other text irrelevant to the analysis of the sentence. There is a range of natural language understanding algorithms that can be used, such as word embeddings, syntactic feature extraction, machine translation, and domain-specific language processing.
Sentence processing can be divided into two categories: rule-based and machine learning-based. Rule-based systems often use complex grammar rules to analyze sentences, while machine learning-based systems learn the rules and can analyze sentences in more complex or natural ways.
The most common rule-based techniques used in sentence processing involve tokenization, noun phrase disambiguation, named entity recognition, part of speech tagging, and sentence splitting. The most common machine learning-based techniques used in sentence processing involve natural language processing tasks such as sentiment analysis, topic modeling, sentence similarity, and text classification.
